# Production Builds with Vite

Vite's build command bundles your application for production using Rolldown, producing optimized, hashed, code-split output in `dist/`.

## Basic Production Build

```bash
# Standard build (output to dist/)
vite build

# Custom mode (loads .env.staging)
vite build --mode staging

# With source maps
vite build --sourcemap

# Custom output directory
vite build --outDir build

# Watch mode for incremental rebuilds
vite build --watch
```

## Build Configuration

```typescript
import { defineConfig } from 'vite';

export default defineConfig({
  build: {
    target: 'es2020',                 // Browser/ES target
    outDir: 'dist',                   // Output directory
    assetsDir: 'assets',              // Asset subdirectory
    assetsInlineLimit: 4096,          // Inline assets under 4kB as base64
    sourcemap: true,                  // Generate source maps
    minify: 'oxc',                    // 'oxc' (default, fastest), 'terser', 'esbuild', false
    cssMinify: 'lightningcss',        // CSS minification engine
    cssCodeSplit: true,               // Per-chunk CSS files
    reportCompressedSize: true,       // Report gzip sizes in output
    chunkSizeWarningLimit: 500,       // Warn on chunks > 500kB
    emptyOutDir: true,                // Clear outDir before build
    copyPublicDir: true,              // Copy public/ to outDir
  },
});
```

See [[vite/config]] for the full config file reference.

## Build Targets and Browser Support

The `build.target` option controls the JavaScript language level of output:

```typescript
export default defineConfig({
  build: {
    // Default: broadly supported baseline features
    target: 'baseline-widely-available',

    // ES version
    target: 'es2020',

    // Specific browsers
    target: ['chrome100', 'firefox115', 'safari16'],

    // Node.js target (for SSR builds)
    target: 'node20',

    // Multiple targets (uses lowest common denominator)
    target: ['es2020', 'edge88', 'firefox78', 'chrome87', 'safari14'],
  },
});
```

For legacy browser support (IE11, older Safari), use the `@vitejs/plugin-legacy` plugin from [[vite/plugins]].

## Library Mode

Build reusable libraries with `build.lib`:

```typescript
import { defineConfig } from 'vite';
import { resolve } from 'path';

export default defineConfig({
  build: {
    lib: {
      entry: resolve(__dirname, 'src/index.ts'),
      name: 'MyLib',                  // UMD global name
      formats: ['es', 'cjs', 'umd'],  // Output formats
      fileName: (format) => `my-lib.${format}.js`,
    },
    rollupOptions: {
      // Externalize deps that shouldn't be bundled
      external: ['react', 'react-dom'],
      output: {
        globals: {
          react: 'React',
          'react-dom': 'ReactDOM',
        },
      },
    },
  },
});
```

Configure `package.json` exports for the library:

```json
{
  "name": "my-lib",
  "type": "module",
  "main": "dist/my-lib.cjs.js",
  "module": "dist/my-lib.es.js",
  "types": "dist/index.d.ts",
  "exports": {
    ".": {
      "import": "./dist/my-lib.es.js",
      "require": "./dist/my-lib.cjs.js"
    }
  },
  "files": ["dist"]
}
```

Note: library mode does not include type declarations. Use [[typescript/compiler]] (`tsc --emitDeclarationOnly`) to generate `.d.ts` files.

## Code Splitting and Chunk Strategies

Vite automatically code-splits on dynamic imports:

```typescript
// Automatic chunk for dynamically imported modules
const module = await import('./heavy-module.ts');

// React lazy loading creates separate chunks
const Dashboard = React.lazy(() => import('./Dashboard'));
```

Customize chunking with `rollupOptions.output.manualChunks`:

```typescript
export default defineConfig({
  build: {
    rollupOptions: {
      output: {
        manualChunks: {
          // Group vendor libs into a shared chunk
          vendor: ['react', 'react-dom', 'react-router-dom'],
          // Separate UI library
          ui: ['@radix-ui/react-dialog', '@radix-ui/react-dropdown-menu'],
        },
      },
    },
  },
});

// Or use a function for dynamic chunking
export default defineConfig({
  build: {
    rollupOptions: {
      output: {
        manualChunks(id) {
          if (id.includes('node_modules')) {
            return 'vendor';
          }
        },
      },
    },
  },
});
```

## Source Maps

Four sourcemap modes for different deployment needs:

```typescript
export default defineConfig({
  build: {
    // false — no source maps (default, smallest output)
    sourcemap: false,

    // true — separate .map files (for error tracking services)
    sourcemap: true,

    // 'inline' — embedded in output files (large, for debugging only)
    sourcemap: 'inline',

    // 'hidden' — .map files generated but not referenced in output
    // Upload to Sentry/Datadog without exposing to browsers
    sourcemap: 'hidden',
  },
});
```

## Minification Options

Vite supports three minifiers:

| Minifier | Setting | Speed | Compression | Notes |
|----------|---------|-------|-------------|-------|
| Oxc | `'oxc'` (default) | Fastest (30-90x vs terser) | Good | Default since Vite 7, Rust-based |
| esbuild | `'esbuild'` | Fast | Good | Go-based, former default |
| Terser | `'terser'` | Slow | Best | Requires `npm i -D terser`, maximum compression |
| Disabled | `false` | N/A | None | For debugging or custom post-processing |

```typescript
export default defineConfig({
  build: {
    minify: 'oxc',     // Default — fast and effective
    // minify: 'terser', // Maximum compression (install terser first)
    // minify: false,    // Disable for debugging
  },
});
```

## SSR Builds

Build server-side rendered applications:

```typescript
// vite.config.ts for SSR
export default defineConfig({
  build: {
    ssr: true,                     // Or specify entry: 'src/entry-server.ts'
    target: 'node20',             // Node.js target
    rollupOptions: {
      input: 'src/entry-server.ts',
    },
  },
});
```

Typical SSR build script:

```bash
# Build client bundle
vite build --outDir dist/client

# Build server bundle
vite build --outDir dist/server --ssr src/entry-server.ts
```

Generate SSR manifest for preloading:

```typescript
export default defineConfig({
  build: {
    ssrManifest: true,   // Generates ssr-manifest.json
    manifest: true,      // Generates manifest.json for asset mapping
  },
});
```

See [[vite/dev-server]] for SSR middleware mode in development.

## Build Manifest for Backend Integration

Generate a manifest mapping source files to hashed output files:

```typescript
export default defineConfig({
  build: {
    manifest: true,   // Generates .vite/manifest.json in outDir
  },
});
```

The manifest maps original file paths to output info:

```json
{
  "src/main.tsx": {
    "file": "assets/main-BkH2gR4a.js",
    "src": "src/main.tsx",
    "isEntry": true,
    "css": ["assets/main-DiwrgTda.css"],
    "imports": ["_vendor-C7BkSa0T.js"]
  }
}
```

Backend frameworks (Rails, Laravel, Django) use this manifest to inject the correct `<script>` and `<link>` tags with cache-busted hashes.

## Preview Production Builds

Locally serve the production build for verification:

```bash
# Preview on default port 4173
vite preview

# Custom port
vite preview --port 8080

# Expose to network
vite preview --host 0.0.0.0
```

The preview server is a simple static file server — it is not a production server. Use it only for local verification before deploying.

## Environment Variables

| Variable | Purpose |
|----------|----------|
| `NODE_ENV` | Set to `production` during `vite build` |
| `VITE_*` | Custom env vars included in the client bundle via `import.meta.env` |

See [[vite/env]] for `.env` file loading, mode configuration, and the `VITE_` prefix convention.
